<H3> <TI>   Further on U.S.-Japan Economic Framework Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on U.S.-Japan Economic Framework Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Schedule for Sectoral Talks </H4>

<F P=102> OW3105031294 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 31 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3105031294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 31 May Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] Sector-by-sector negotiations in the Japan-U.S. 
economic framework talks will resume in Tokyo with negotiations 
on the insurance sector starting on 1 June. Likewise, 
negotiations on automobiles and auto parts will open in 
Washington on 2 June, and those on government procurement of 
telecommunications equipment and medical equipment in Tokyo on 3 
and 7 June, respectively. 
  In the automobile negotiations, U.S. Under Secretary of 
Commerce Jeffrey Garten will come to Japan in the week of 6 
June, and hold vice ministerial-level talks with Sozaburo 
Okamatsu, deputy vice minister of international trade and 
industry. 
  Apart from the above three priority sectors, discussions on 
intellectual property rights, one of the other five sectors the 
United States wants to negotiate, will also begin in Washington 
around 10 June. 
  After the recent informal meetings in Washington which 
resulted in the decision to resume the framework talks, 
working-level talks are being held to finalize concrete points 
of agreement for each sector. 
  Of the three priority sectors, the issue of liberalizing 
insurance covering injury and illness, where U.S. companies have 
an advantage, is expected to be the focal issue in insurance 
sector negotiations. 
  Negotiations on government procurement and automobiles and 
auto parts will concentrate on the issue of "objective 
criteria," on which no conclusion was reached in previous 
unofficial discussions. 
  On intellectual property rights, copyright protection for 
computer software, and standardization of the patent systems in 
Japan and the United States are expected to be the topics of 
discussion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-27322 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas105__a94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-105-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on U.S.-Japan Economic Framework Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on U.S.-Japan Economic Framework Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Focal Issue To Be Objective Criteria </H4>

<F P=102> OW3105065294 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 30 May 
94 Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3105065294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Shigeru Komago] </F>
  [Text] Washington, 29 May -- After the resumption of 
sector-by-sector negotiations in the Japanese-U.S. economic 
framework talks, the question of whether "figures for the 
future" should be included as objective criteria is expected to 
be a focal issue once again. If the United States insists on 
numerical indicators for such supplementary categories as the 
increase in stores selling foreign products, which it is 
proposing in place of "numerical targets," conflict may arise 
again. This may even undermine the basic agreement already 
reached at unofficial consultations on the "participation and 
sales increases of foreign products." The following looks at 
the points of agreement and remaining differences between Japan 
and the United States on the eve of reopening the negotiations. 
Points of Agreement [subhead] 
  According to sources in the Japanese and U.S. negotiating 
teams, compared to the time that the framework talks broke down 
last February, both sides compromised at the recent unofficial 
meetings which resulted in the resumption of negotiations. In 
the first place, the United States backed off on its demand for 
"numerical targets" which set a specific amount of increase in 
imports or sales until a specific point in time in the future -- 
the greatest stumbling block in the talks. It also did not ask 
for a deadline for concluding the talks. 
  Japan also compromised on the issue of the objective of the 
framework talks, giving up its stand of July 1993 that the talks 
are meant to "effect an overall increase" in the participation 
and sales of competitive foreign products in the Japanese 
market, and accepting "sector-by-sector increases" in market 
participation and sales as the negotiations' objective. While 
some people are still negative about sales increase in 
insurance, this is still a major concession on Japan's part 
compared to its position last February that "we cannot promise 
any increase in the future." 
  In short, the United States gave up its demand to set 
numerical targets for imports and sales, while Japan compromised 
on the framework talks' objective by accepting sector-by-sector 
increases. 
Differences and Ambiguous Points [subhead] 
  In previous sector-by-sector negotiations, the question of 
the application of the objective criteria was not resolved. 
Instead of insisting on its previous position that this should 
apply only to "past results," Japan has now indicated a 
willingness to accept the application of such criteria on the 
number of dealers, past sales trends, and other "indicators" of 
expanded market opportunities, which it opposed last February. 
  Taking advantage of this concession, the United States is 
now 
asking for the inclusion of "figures for the future" with regard 
to the supplementary indicators which do not directly reflect 
imports and sales, and this is considered to be merely a 
roundabout form of "seminumerical targets." A typical example 
of this is the proposal on figures for the future on the "number 
of dealers of foreign products" and so forth in the negotiations 
on automobiles and auto parts. 
  In government procurement -- for instance, 
telecommunications 
-- which is entirely under government control, the United States 
may renew its demand to set future numerical indicators for the 
"procurement volume" itself. 
  If the United States insists on such proposals and Japan 
refuses stubbornly, saying "these are numerical targets," the 
negotiations may break down again. However, certain U.S. 
sources claim that "bringing up future numerical indicators 
again for the supplementary categories is merely a negotiating 
technique of the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative 
(USTR)." They say that it is doubtful that the United States 
will insist on such proposals at the risk of another round of 
the depreciation of the dollar. It is possible that the United 
States will compromise further on numerical targets at the 
sector-by-sector negotiations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-27323 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas105__a94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-105-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on U.S.-Japan Economic Framework Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on U.S.-Japan Economic Framework Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kantor Criticized Over Car Dealers </H4>

<F P=102> OW2705135694 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 27 May 94 
Morning Edition p 11--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2705135694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor has 
demanded that Japan fulfill its commitment to increase the 
number of dealers in foreign cars, an issue which was regarded 
as pending in the bilateral economic framework talks. 
Commenting on this, a negotiator for the Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry [MITI] criticized the demand as 
follows: 1) The Kantor demand goes against the Japan-U.S. 
accord to "rule out target figures"; and 2) each auto dealer is 
supposed to be free to make the decision whether or not to deal 
in foreign-made models, and the government must not intervene in 
their business affairs. 
  The MITI negotiator noted his concern over Kantor's remark, 
saying: "Even if the framework talks are resumed, the two 
nations may fall into the same dilemma." 
  The Japanese Government agrees on using the number of 
dealers 
in foreign cars as one of several "objective criteria" to 
evaluate the openness of the Japanese auto market. However, 
Japan says the criteria must be used to review present 
circumstances and past records, and Kantor's demand for "future 
commitment" is nothing but a demand for a numerical target. 
  In the bilateral accord on the resumption of the framework 
talks, a commitment on auto sales was drawn up on the same lines 
as one on the mobile phone market. 
  The MITI negotiator, however, said: "While the government 
does have control over access to the mobile phone market, auto 
sales is a liberal industrial field run by the business sector. 
The government exercises very different authority in each 
field." 
  The United States has been demanding that Japan honor its 
commitment to increase the number of dealers in foreign cars. 
Japanese negotiators feel Kantor's remarks indicated the United 
States has no intention of changing its negotiation policies 
even after the latest accord. 
  Some quarters in the government are voicing frustration with 
the bilateral accord on the resumption of framework talks, 
saying: "The accord was made hastily. Consequently it is 
inadequate and may be open to misinterpretation by the United 
States." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

