<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on U.S.-Japan Economic Framework Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on U.S.-Japan Economic Framework Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    MITI Cuts Numerical Targets Again </H4>

<F P=102> OW2905074094 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 29 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2905074094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 29 May Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] On 27 May, a top Ministry of International Trade 
and Industry [MITI] official declared: "We will not promise 
numbers which are determined by market mechanisms." He made 
this remark in reference to the fact the numerical targets' 
definition is still not clear even though Japan and the United 
States have agreed not to include numerical targets as an 
objective criteria measure in the Japan-U.S. economic talks, 
which are due to resume soon. He said even when the United 
States asks for something that comes close to numerical targets 
-- like a growth rate measure --, Japan will reject it at the 
sector-by-sector talks. 
  Asked about the possibility that at the automobile and auto 
part talks, the United States might ask to set targets on the 
number of auto dealers, he said: "We cannot make any promise on 
something that is out of the government's reach." 

</TEXT>

