<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plan for Radioactive Waste Disposal Agreed With Moscow </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Plan for Radioactive Waste Disposal Agreed With Moscow </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3005023694 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 29 May 94 
Morning Edition p 1 -- FOR OOFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3005023694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Both the Japanese and Russian Governments, which 
have been discussing measures to prevent Moscow from resuming 
dumping of radioactive waste into the sea, have agreed to 
dispose of radioactive waste by constructing small facilities 
which float on the water. The design is currently being worked 
out. Construction is expected to begin this summer and be 
finished early next year. Since the Russian Government has 
pledged "not to resume dumping into waters earlier than the 
facilities are completed," radioactive waste dumping into the 
Sea of Japan will be avoided for the time being if the plan 
proceeds smoothly. 
  Russia has asked Japan to help construct such facilities. 
The two governments have been coordinating details of the plan. 
  The facilities will be constructed in a harbor in the 
suburbs 
of Vladivostok, and they are capable of storing approximately 
800 tons of radioactive waste. Three tanks -- for storing, 
processing, and solidifying radioactive waste -- will be 
installed on a ship, and the waste will be put in drums. 
Construction costs are expected to reach $20 or $30 million and 
will be covered by Japan's $100-million program for assisting 
the denuclearization of the former Soviet Union. This plan is 
regarded as an emergency measure to prevent dumping of 
radioactive waste into the sea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

