<H3> <TI>   Kakizawa Voices Concern on DPRK Inspections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kakizawa Voices Concern on DPRK Inspections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW3105025494 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 31 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3105025494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 30 May Evening Edition] </F>
  [Text] On the morning of 30 May, the Budget Committee of 
the House of Representatives continued its comprehensive 
interpellations on the fiscal 1994 draft budget. At this 
session, Yoshio Hachiro (of the Social Democratic Party of Japan 
[SDPJ]) raised the question of how the government intended to 
deal with the breach between the DPRK [Democratic Poeple's 
Republic of Korea] and the International Atomic Energy Agency 
(IAEA) on consultaions on the nuclear inspection issue. 
  In reply, Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa stated: "They are 
engaged in extracting fuel rods from the five-megawatt 
experimental nuclear reactor. If this operation should 
continue, it would become -- within two or three days -- 
difficult to carry out further inspection. And we are concerned 
about this." 
  His comments indicated that the government is seriously 
concerned about the situation. 
  He added: "We have made proposals in various forms to North 
Korea, asking for its sincere handling of the issue. And to 
carry out further inspection, consultations are being held 
between the United States and the DPRK, between Japan, the 
United States, and the ROK, and also with China." 
  His remarks disclosed the fact that consultations are 
currently being held on the issue among various countries. 

</TEXT>

