<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SDPJ Delegation To Visit DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    SDPJ Delegation To Visit DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2805015494 Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN in Japanese 26 May 94 
Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2805015494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo SANKEI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] plans 
to send a delegation of its Diet members to North Korea in June. 
This was revealed by SDPJ Secretary General Wataru Kubo in an 
interview with SANKEI SHIMBUN on 25 May. If the plan is 
realized, the party will ask North Korea to refrain from 
engaging in its alleged nuclear arms development program. It 
will also call for resumption of talks on normalizing Japan-DPRK 
relations. 
  Although the SDPJ has been on friendly terms with the 
Workers 
Party of Korea, it has stopped sending formal delegations since 
last August when it joined the coalition as a member of the 
former Hosokawa administration. But since the SPDJ bolted the 
coalition and "there are no more restrictions as a ruling party" 
(according to a SDPJ official), the SDPJ is now holding informal 
negotiations with North Korea on a plan to send a delegation led 
by Secretary General Kubo as soon as meetings with President 
Kim Il-song and other leaders are arranged. 

</TEXT>

