<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mitsubishi, Hitachi Cooperate on Flash Memory </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mitsubishi, Hitachi Cooperate on Flash Memory </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0228A Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 12 May 94 
p 17--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0228A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] Mitsubishi Electric will jointly develop with 
Hitachi flash memory (read-only memory which can be 
electronically erased and rewritten all at once) which is the 
next-generation leading memory. They will employ the Mitsubishi 
method in 16-megabit products and the Hitachi method in 
64-megabit products, develop and sell uniform specification 
products. The aim is to rival Toshiba which is leading the flash 
memory market by tieups with U.S. and South Korean 
manufacturers. Since Toshiba, Hitachi, and Mitsubishi are 
respectively proceeding with development of unique methods with 
different specifications for flash memory, making their own 
method the de facto standard such as the format for VTR [video 
tape recorders] has become a big task for survival in the 
market. Various companies are competing furiously as they 
consider flash memory the next big product after DRAM [dynamic 
random-access memory] (dynamic read and write memory necessary 
for memory storage operations). However, it smacks of just talk 
in advance and there are some rather vague parts such as 
realistically to what applications will it be most directed? 
Moreover, viewed internationally, since the large U.S. 
semiconductor manufacturer Intel now hold the greatest market 
share, it seems a big task will be how to destroy the Intel 
stronghold. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

